\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}
Nocturnal boundary layer transitions present a notorious modeling challenge due to the highly non-linear, non-equilibrium coupling between atmospheric dynamics, surface energy budgets, and microphysical turbulence scales. This work provides a rigorous Geometric Singular Perturbation Theory (GSPT) characterization of these transitions, mapping the stable boundary layer (SBL) state-space trajectories as constrained flows on a low-dimensional manifold.
The manuscript is organized as a unified applied-mathematics stack: governing system, fast-slow decomposition, critical manifold geometry, regularization, regime-transition geometry, and numerical experiments.

